  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects include:\n\n1. Financial institutions must:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (USA)\n- European Union's AML Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n\n3. Typical requirements involve:\n- Customer due diligence\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting large or suspicious transactions\n- Implementing risk-based compliance systems\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThese regulations apply to banks, credit unions, money transfer services, cryptocurrency exchanges, and other financial institutions.",
